</p><p><big>{{Principal Doctrine 37}}</big>
</p><p>== Analysis ==
</p><p>In this, relatively lengthy [[Principal Doctrines|Doctrine]], [[Epicurus]] unfolds his complex, multipartite understanding of the "Nature of [[Justice]]": what it is, what it is based on, how it changes, how it is conceived. To follow Epicurus' logical exposition one item at a time:
</p><p>A. Epicurus begins with what he considers "natural" justice, or the "justice of nature":
</p>
<ul><li> Certain (kinds of) actions have been held to be just. Instead of embarking on argumentation (which he would have considered superfluous), Epicurus defers to a broad, moral/historical sense of precedent, a notion of Common Law, of a commonly held understanding among many people. This may be the Epicurean (approximate) equivalent of "self-evident truths", albeit not conferred by [[gods|deity]], but self-evident because they are commonly shared among humans.
</li></ul>
<ul><li> These just actions have been confirmed. Here, Epicurus tellingly uses the term ''epimartyria'', i.e. the same term he uses routinely to signify the mental process by which sensory perceptions in general are confirmed. As above, it was not some god who decreed these moral truths, but they stand as solid as facts, because human experience has confirmed them since time immemorial.
</li></ul>
<ul><li> These actions have been confirmed as just expressly because they are beneficial. Thus the cornerstone of the Epicurean understanding of justice is instrumental, "utilitarian" (yet not, of course, in the sense of modern, economic, "upper-case" Utilitarianism), as it views justice  not as something inherently good in the abstract (Cf. [[Principal Doctrine 23]]), but as something useful for the benefits it confers.
</li></ul>
<ul><li> These confirmed actions are beneficial because they serve the needs of human association'><font color='#800000'>in</font></a>&nbsp;</p><br><p><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:in&amp;action=edit'><font color='#cc6600'>edit</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></span><span><p class='script150'><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:everyday' title='Dictionary empty: use link below:/→,2:/→,3:/What is confirmed by testimony,6:/for,7:the,8:needs,9:/of,10:/→,11:mutual,12:association,13:/→,15:to be,17:/has (the quality of),18:/[being],19:in,20:/the [domain],22:/→,23:/→,24:whether,26:/→,27:the same,28:/[may happen] to everyone,29:/→,30:/(or),33:/→,34:/→,35:/If,36:on the other hand,37:/→,38:/[one] establishes (some) [law],39:/→,40:/→,41:/[but it does not] result,42:/→,43:in,44:that which is,45:beneficial,46:/→,47:for,48:mutual,49:association,50:/[this] no longer,51:/→,52:/[has] the,53:/→,54:/→,55:/nature [of justice],56:/→,57:/And even if,58:/→,59:/that which is [beneficial],60:according to,61:/→,62:/justice [may change for the worse],63:/→,64:/→,65:while,66:/(for) some [time],67:/→,69:/preconception (of justice),70:/(it) may fit,71:/→,72:nonetheless,73:/(for) that,68:/[may have fit] the,70:/→,74:/→,76:/(it) was,77:just,78:to those who,79:/[do] not [agitate themselves],80:/→,81:/[with] empty [shouts],82:/→,83:/→,85:/plainly [look at],86:/→,87:the,88:facts,89:/→</interlinear>
</li></ul>
<p>== Translation ==
</p><p><big>{{Principal Doctrine 37}}</big>
</p><p>== Analysis ==
</p><p>In this, relatively lengthy [[Principal Doctrines|Doctrine]], [[Epicurus]] unfolds his complex, multipartite understanding of the "Nature of [[Justice]]": what it is, what it is based on, how it changes, how it is conceived. To follow Epicurus' logical exposition one item at a time:
</p><p>A. Epicurus begins with what he considers "natural" justice, or the "justice of nature":
</p>
<ul><li> Certain (kinds of) actions have been held to be just. Instead of embarking on argumentation (which he would have considered superfluous), Epicurus defers to a broad, moral/historical sense of precedent, a notion of Common Law, of a commonly held understanding among many people. This may be the Epicurean (approximate) equivalent of "self-evident truths", albeit not conferred by [[gods|deity]], but self-evident because they are commonly shared among humans.
</li></ul>
<ul><li> These just actions have been confirmed. Here, Epicurus tellingly uses the term ''epimartyria'', i.e. the same term he uses routinely to signify the mental process by which sensory perceptions in general are confirmed. As above, it was not some god who decreed these moral truths, but they stand as solid as facts, because human experience has confirmed them since time immemorial.
</li></ul>
<ul><li> These actions have been confirmed as just expressly because they are beneficial. Thus the cornerstone of the Epicurean understanding of justice is instrumental, "utilitarian" (yet not, of course, in the sense of modern, economic, "upper-case" Utilitarianism), as it views justice  not as something inherently good in the abstract (Cf. [[Principal Doctrine 23]]), but as something useful for the benefits it confers.
</li></ul>
<ul><li> These confirmed actions are beneficial because they serve the needs of human association'><font color='#800000'>everyday</font></a>&nbsp;</p><br><p><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:everyday&amp;action=edit'><font color='#cc6600'>edit</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></span><span><p class='script150'><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:parlance' title='Dictionary empty: use link below:/→,2:/→,3:/What is confirmed by testimony,6:/for,7:the,8:needs,9:/of,10:/→,11:mutual,12:association,13:/→,15:to be,17:/has (the quality of),18:/[being],19:in,20:/the [domain],22:/→,23:/→,24:whether,26:/→,27:the same,28:/[may happen] to everyone,29:/→,30:/(or),33:/→,34:/→,35:/If,36:on the other hand,37:/→,38:/[one] establishes (some) [law],39:/→,40:/→,41:/[but it does not] result,42:/→,43:in,44:that which is,45:beneficial,46:/→,47:for,48:mutual,49:association,50:/[this] no longer,51:/→,52:/[has] the,53:/→,54:/→,55:/nature [of justice],56:/→,57:/And even if,58:/→,59:/that which is [beneficial],60:according to,61:/→,62:/justice [may change for the worse],63:/→,64:/→,65:while,66:/(for) some [time],67:/→,69:/preconception (of justice),70:/(it) may fit,71:/→,72:nonetheless,73:/(for) that,68:/[may have fit] the,70:/→,74:/→,76:/(it) was,77:just,78:to those who,79:/[do] not [agitate themselves],80:/→,81:/[with] empty [shouts],82:/→,83:/→,85:/plainly [look at],86:/→,87:the,88:facts,89:/→</interlinear>
