<ul><li> These actions have been confirmed as just expressly because they are beneficial. Thus the cornerstone of the Epicurean understanding of justice is instrumental, "utilitarian" (yet not, of course, in the sense of modern, economic, "upper-case" Utilitarianism), as it views justice  not as something inherently good in the abstract (Cf. [[Principal Doctrine 23]]), but as something useful for the benefits it confers.
</li></ul>
