<ul><li> Certain (kinds of) actions have been held to be just. Instead of embarking on argumentation (which he would have considered superfluous), Epicurus defers to a broad, moral/historical sense of precedent, a notion of Common Law, of a commonly held understanding among many people. This may be the Epicurean (approximate) equivalent of "self-evident truths", albeit not conferred by [[gods|deity]], but self-evident because they are commonly shared among humans.
